-tags: [technical-writing, ai, documentation]
+description: "AI product docs now serve developers, answer engines, and agents. I break down the writing rules that changed, with examples from OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, MCP, and llms.txt."
+tags: [technical-writing, ai, developer-experience, documentation]
 status: published
 ---
 
-AI product docs go stale faster than docs for ordinary software because the product itself is probabilistic, model-dependent, and often assembled from prompts, tools, retrieval, and guardrails that change underneath the UI. I think the old playbook for technical writing breaks the minute a team documents an AI feature as if it were a stable button with deterministic output. Readers need a map of behavior, limits, and change risk, not polished feature copy.
+Technical writing for AI products changed when documentation stopped being passive reference material and started acting like runtime input. A bad paragraph in a docs site used to confuse a reader. A bad tool description now confuses a model, triggers the wrong action, or hides the right one from the interface entirely.
 
-**Short answer:** Technical writing for AI products now requires five shifts. I document behavior ranges instead of fixed outcomes, version prompts and model assumptions explicitly, tie examples to eval criteria, explain tool and context boundaries, and publish failure modes as first-class product information. OpenAI recommends pinning production systems to model snapshots and building evals for prompt behavior, Anthropic recommends defining success criteria before prompt iteration, and MCP makes tool and context surfaces part of the product contract, not hidden implementation details.
+I think most advice on AI documentation is still one generation behind the product surface. People still talk about blog-style explainers, clean navigation, and a docs search box. Those still matter. The harder job now is writing documentation that works for three readers at once: a human developer, a chat-based answer engine, and an agent runtime that reads metadata, schemas, and machine-friendly markdown directly.
 
-## Rule one: document behavior, not promises
+**Short answer:** Technical writing for AI products now has to cover three layers at once: human comprehension, model-readable structure, and execution-safe metadata. I still start with scope, audience, and task outcome, which Google's technical writing course treats as fundamentals, but I now add tool descriptions, JSON schemas, markdown twins, and `llms.txt` files because modern AI systems read those surfaces directly. Teams that treat those surfaces as secondary usually ship confusing products.
 
-I see weak AI docs make the same mistake over and over. They describe what the product is supposed to do, then skip what it usually does, what it sometimes does, and what it cannot safely do. That gap matters more in AI than anywhere else because the output can shift across model versions, prompt changes, retrieval quality, or tool availability.
+## Old documentation rules still matter, but the output surface changed
 
-OpenAI's [prompt engineering guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/prompt-engineering) states plainly that model output is non-deterministic and recommends pinning production apps to specific model snapshots while building evals that monitor prompt behavior. Anthropic's [prompt engineering overview](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/prompt-engineering) starts even earlier: define success criteria, create empirical tests, then improve prompts. Both documents imply the same writing rule. Product docs need to describe the behavioral envelope around a feature, not just its ideal case.
+Google's technical writing guidance still holds up unusually well. Google says a strong document should state scope and non-scope, define the audience, and summarize key points at the start. Google also recommends prompts that specify role, target audience, document type, goal, style, and constraints when using LLMs for drafting or revision. I read that less as generic writing advice and more as a checklist for every AI product surface I ship, because the same missing context hurts both humans and models. A vague page produces vague answers. A vague tool description produces wrong tool calls. A vague schema produces structured nonsense that still passes validation.
 
-I write AI docs with language like "best for," "fails when," "tested against," and "requires" because those phrases tell the truth. "Generates support replies" is weak. "Generates first-draft replies for password resets, refunds, and billing questions when account context is present; routes edge cases to humans" is useful. Readers can build with the second sentence. They cannot budget risk from the first.
+Google makes another point that I agree with from experience: writing is how engineers figure out what they mean. I have seen AI teams try to skip that work by asking a model for a first draft before anyone has nailed the product contract. Resulting docs often look polished and still fail at the one thing the user needs, which is a precise statement of what the system accepts, returns, refuses, and guarantees.
 
-My take is that AI companies overuse capability language because marketing pressure leaks into docs. That choice looks harmless until a user assumes reliability the system never had. Once that happens, support inherits the ambiguity and the docs lose authority.
+## Three readers now sit inside every serious AI docs set
 
-## Rule two: version the invisible parts
+I organize AI product documentation around three readers:
 
-Prompt text, model snapshots, retrieval logic, tool permissions, and output schemas often matter more than the visible feature name. Old-school SaaS docs could hide plenty of internals because the user only needed the API shape. AI products rarely get that luxury.
+| Surface | Primary reader | What good writing has to do |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| Guides, tutorials, changelogs | Human developer | Explain tasks, tradeoffs, limits, and migration paths quickly |
+| Searchable markdown, answer-engine-friendly pages | Chat interfaces and retrieval systems | Expose dense facts in extractable form with low ambiguity |
+| Tool metadata, schemas, prompts, `llms.txt`, MCP descriptors | Agents and model runtimes | Make invocation boundaries, arguments, side effects, and safe usage explicit |
 
-OpenAI's [evaluation best practices guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/evaluation-best-practices) argues for eval-driven development because generative systems vary even under the same input. OpenAI's [model selection guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/model-selection/principles) also recommends starting from an accuracy target and a real evaluation dataset. That means docs cannot treat "uses GPT-5" or "powered by Claude" as sufficient technical detail. Readers need to know what version was tested, what quality bar the team used, and what changed when a model or prompt was updated.
+That split sounds obvious once stated, yet many teams still write as if only the first row exists. OpenAI's Apps SDK documentation states that ChatGPT decides when to call a connector based on the metadata you provide, and recommends testing names, descriptions, and parameter docs against a labeled prompt set with direct, indirect, and negative prompts. OpenAI's app submission rules go even further and call MCP tools the manual for ChatGPT to use your app. That is not marketing language. That is an operational fact. Metadata is documentation now.
 
-I have started treating prompt and model changes as documentation events, not just engineering events. A release note that says "improved answer quality" tells me almost nothing. A note that says "customer-support drafting now runs on a pinned model snapshot with a revised refusal prompt and stricter JSON schema validation; response style changed for billing disputes" gives an operator something concrete to re-test.
+My take is blunt: if a model reads a field, that field belongs to the technical writing surface. Product teams often leave those fields to whoever implemented the endpoint. That is how you end up with a tool called `run_action_v2`, a description that hides side effects, and parameter docs that leak internal naming instead of task intent.
 
-My own rule is simple: if a change can alter output shape, latency, refusal behavior, or tool choice, it deserves documentation. AI teams often bury those changes because they are not obvious UI work. Users feel them anyway.
+## Tool descriptions need the same editorial rigor as public docs
 
-## Rule three: examples need eval context
+OpenAI's metadata guide says names, descriptions, and parameter docs affect recall and accidental activation. OpenAI also says you should change one metadata field at a time, replay a golden prompt set, and track precision and recall. That is a real editorial workflow. Anthropic reaches a similar place from the prompting side. Anthropic recommends explicit instructions, relevant examples, and clear structure with XML tags so Claude can separate instructions, context, and inputs reliably.
 
-Examples carry more weight in AI docs than in traditional docs because users study them for steering clues. Prompt phrasing, XML tags, field ordering, and schema constraints all influence output. OpenAI's [structured outputs guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/structured-outputs) exists because "return JSON" is not enough when downstream systems need a schema-conformant response. Anthropic's [tool use overview](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/agents-and-tools/tool-use/overview) shows how tool descriptions and input schemas shape model behavior during execution.
+Plenty of teams still write tool docs like database column comments. I think that habit is expensive. A tool description now does four jobs at once:
 
-That changes how I write examples. I do not publish a prompt or code sample without saying what success looked like when it was tested. A serious example needs at least three things:
+1. It tells the model when the tool should run.
+2. It tells the model when the tool should not run.
+3. It tells the user what the tool can affect.
+4. It gives reviewers enough precision to catch unsafe behavior.
 
-- The exact input or schema that was tested.
-- The boundary conditions, such as context available, tools enabled, or language assumptions.
-- The intended success criterion, such as classification accuracy, function-call correctness, or valid JSON rate.
+OpenAI's submission rules explicitly reject misleading, promotional, or manipulative model-readable fields. Descriptions cannot tell the model to prefer one tool over others. They must match behavior, request minimal input, and make side effects obvious. MCP pushes the same direction at the protocol level. The spec says tools are model-controlled, recommends a human in the loop for denial and confirmation, and requires explicit schemas around inputs. That means writers cannot hide behind "the model will infer it." The protocol expects the opposite.
 
-Readers copy examples into production. Leaving out the test context is a quiet way to ship broken guidance. I have seen teams publish cheerful playground snippets that only work because the author had hidden setup in local state or a permissive system prompt. That kind of example converts badly and wastes engineering time on the buyer side.
+I have seen this go wrong in a specific way on agent projects. Teams write a broad tool description to improve discovery, the model overfires, and then someone patches the harness with brittle rules to suppress calls. I covered the harness side of that problem in my post on [agent infrastructure](/blog/agent-harnesses/). Good metadata often removes a lot of ugly control logic from the runtime.
 
-One non-obvious lesson from AI docs work: examples now do double duty as education and as evaluation fixtures. A strong sample prompt can seed a test set. A weak sample prompt teaches users the wrong abstraction and quietly normalizes brittle behavior.
+## Machine-readable docs are no longer optional for AI products
 
-## Rule four: tool and context boundaries belong in the docs
+One rule changed more than any other: HTML alone is no longer enough. OpenAI publishes `llms.txt` indexes and markdown twins for its developer docs. Google's Gemini API docs publish an `llms.txt` file too. The `llms.txt` proposal exists for a practical reason: large models do poorly when forced to infer structure from full websites full of navigation chrome, scripts, and layout noise. The proposal recommends a root `/llms.txt` file plus markdown versions of pages so systems can find concise, machine-usable source material fast.
 
-Agent products made this rule impossible to ignore. Once a model can call tools, browse, read files, or reach internal data sources, documentation has to explain the operating boundary around that behavior.
+That pattern matters because AI products increasingly get evaluated by systems that never browse your site like a person. They ingest a markdown export, a tool schema, or a curated list of docs. OpenAI's `llms.txt` page literally says each Apps SDK page has a markdown twin for direct ingestion. Google exposes a similar docs map for Gemini. Those vendors are telling writers exactly how they expect machine readers to consume documentation.
 
-The [MCP architecture overview](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/architecture) explains that MCP servers expose tools, resources, and prompts to an AI host through a client-server protocol. Anthropic's [tool use overview](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/agents-and-tools/tool-use/overview) describes the execution loop explicitly: the model requests a tool, the application executes it, then returns the result. Neither source treats tool access as magic. Both describe it as a contract surface with schemas, permissions, and execution flow.
+I think many teams are still treating `llms.txt` as a visibility hack. That is too shallow. Proper machine-readable docs force editorial discipline. You have to decide which files deserve first-class placement, what each link means, which details are optional, and what an external system can safely assume without the rest of the site chrome. That editing work usually improves the human docs too.
 
-Docs for AI products need the same discipline. I want to know:
+## Structure beats eloquence in AI product docs
 
-- Which tools are available in a given mode or plan.
-- What data the model can read directly, retrieve indirectly, or never access.
-- What happens when a tool fails, times out, or returns partial results.
-- Whether outputs are synthesized from retrieved content, live tool calls, or model prior knowledge.
+Anthropic's prompting guidance says XML tags reduce misinterpretation, 3 to 5 examples usually work best, and placing long-form data above the query can improve response quality. Anthropic also cites tests where putting queries at the end improves quality by up to 30% for complex multi-document inputs. Those details matter because they reveal what models reward: explicit segmentation, stable labels, and predictable document shape.
 
-I wrote about the runtime layer around these systems in my post on [agent harnesses](/blog/agent-harnesses/). That harness logic becomes part of the user experience long before buyers learn the term. When docs skip those boundaries, users blame the model for failures that really belong to orchestration and permissions.
+Writing for AI products therefore rewards structure more than flourish. I still care about sentence rhythm, but I care more about whether a model can separate scope from caveat, example from rule, and supported path from deprecated path. Google advises writers to summarize key points at the start because readers are busy. That recommendation now pulls double duty. Readers skim intros. Retrieval systems often overweight them.
 
-## Rule five: failure modes need public language
+My strongest editorial bias here is simple: front-load the contract. Put the supported model list, rate limits, required headers, schema guarantees, refusal behavior, and side-effect boundaries where a parser and a tired engineer can both find them in seconds. I made the same argument in my piece on [structured outputs and function calling](/blog/structured-outputs-llms-json-mode-function-calling/). A schema only helps if the surrounding documentation tells people what the schema does not guarantee.
 
-Teams still treat failure modes like embarrassing edge cases that belong in internal runbooks. I think that instinct is wrong for AI products. Failure modes are part of the feature definition.
+## Claims now need tighter audit trails
 
-OpenAI's eval guidance pushes teams to log everything, test edge cases, and calibrate automated metrics against human judgment. That advice points to a documentation standard too. If multilingual inputs, missing context, conflicting tool outputs, or malformed schemas break quality, say so in the docs. If the system is tuned for extraction and weak at synthesis, say that too. Precision saves more trust than broad promises ever will.
+AI docs rot faster than most software docs because the underlying behavior moves faster. Model names change. Beta headers disappear. Tool annotations gain new meaning. A loose claim that would have survived for a year in a database article can become wrong in a month in an AI article.
 
-I prefer a compact "known limits" section near setup or API reference pages. Good limit statements answer three questions quickly: what fails, how to detect it, and what fallback to use. Readers forgive limits they can plan around. Readers do not forgive silent failure.
+OpenAI's app rules, Anthropic's prompting guides, and the MCP specification all keep emphasizing explicitness, validation, and auditable behavior. MCP says clients should validate tool results, log tool usage, show inputs before sensitive calls, and confirm risky operations with the user. OpenAI says tool inputs should be minimal and purpose-driven. Anthropic says prompt engineering should start with clear success criteria and empirical tests. Taken together, those documents point to one writing rule I wish more teams followed: every operational claim in AI docs should map to a testable behavior, not just a plausible sentence.
 
-One of the most common briefs I get from AI infrastructure teams is some version of "we shipped the feature, but users do not know when to trust it." Writing solves part of that problem only when the team is willing to document uncomfortable truths. If you need someone to write that kind of material with engineering-level specificity, [my work page](/work) shows the sort of depth I aim for.
+I now write AI product docs the same way I write good changelogs: every important sentence should help someone make a decision. My changelog piece on [writing release notes developers actually read](/blog/how-to-write-a-changelog-developers-actually-read/) came from the same instinct. Users do not need broad reassurance. Users need to know what changed, what is stable, what can break, and what the migration path looks like.
 
-## Old docs patterns that actively hurt AI products
+## The new writing workflow I would enforce on an AI product team
 
-Some patterns that are merely mediocre in ordinary software become damaging in AI docs:
-
-- Feature-summary intros with no tested scope.
-- Playground examples without model version or schema constraints.
-- API docs that hide refusal behavior, fallback logic, or retry semantics.
-- Release notes that say "quality improvements" without naming the changed prompt, model, or evaluation target.
-- Architecture diagrams that omit retrieval, ranking, or tool execution steps.
-
-I have seen each one create avoidable support load. Engineers start debugging the wrong layer because the docs presented the system as simpler than it really is. Buyers evaluating the product often read that simplification as immaturity.
-
-My strongest opinion here is that documentation quality for AI products now reveals product maturity faster than the homepage does. Weak docs signal that the team has not operationalized evals, versioning, or boundaries yet. Strong docs signal the opposite.
-
-## What I would publish for any serious AI feature
-
-When I work on AI product documentation, I want every feature page to answer a concrete operational checklist:
+If I owned technical writing for an AI product today, I would enforce this workflow:
 
-1. What exact task is the system designed to handle?
-2. What model, prompt, schema, or routing assumptions does the behavior depend on?
-3. What data sources or tools shape the answer?
-4. How was quality evaluated?
-5. What are the known failure modes and fallback paths?
-6. What changed in the latest update that could affect output or integration behavior?
-
-Traditional software docs could get away with stopping at inputs and outputs. AI products need provenance and quality context too. Readers are making adoption decisions under uncertainty. Good docs reduce that uncertainty enough for them to keep going.
-
-## Documentation now sits closer to operations
-
-The deeper shift is organizational. AI documentation is moving closer to product operations than classic documentation usually does. Prompt changes, eval regressions, schema drift, and tool permission changes all have user-facing consequences. Somebody has to narrate those consequences clearly and fast.
+1. Define the contract first. Document scope, non-scope, audience, task outcome, and known failure modes before anyone polishes prose.
+2. Split the docs set by runtime surface. Human guide pages, tool metadata, schemas, and machine-readable exports should each get an explicit owner.
+3. Test metadata like product behavior. Replay direct, indirect, and negative prompts against tool descriptions the way OpenAI recommends.
+4. Publish machine-readable entry points. Ship markdown twins where possible and maintain a curated `llms.txt` file instead of expecting crawlers to infer your hierarchy.
+5. Treat examples as part of the API contract. Anthropic's guidance on structured examples is right. Weak examples teach the model weak habits.
+6. Keep every risky action legible. Side effects, destructive operations, and public posting paths should be obvious from names, descriptions, and annotations.
 
-That is why I think the new rules are less about style and more about systems thinking. A writer covering AI products needs to understand prompt structure, evaluation design, context boundaries, and release discipline well enough to ask annoying questions. Which model snapshot? Which eval? Which tool path? Which failure condition? Which fallback? I do not think a writer can stay useful here by polishing language after the fact.
+A limitation belongs here too. Some products are still too volatile for polished long-form docs to keep up. Early-stage agent products change faster than any writer can revise public pages. Teams in that phase still need internal contract docs and schema discipline. Public docs can lag a little. Runtime surfaces cannot.
 
-I covered adjacent parts of that operational reality in my pieces on [structured outputs for LLMs](/blog/structured-outputs-llms-json-mode-function-calling/) and [the Model Context Protocol](/blog/model-context-protocol-explained/). Both topics push documentation toward sharper contracts. That trend is going to continue because AI products keep exposing more of their internals as user-visible behavior.
+Technical writing for AI companies is also the kind of work I do professionally, and the common failure pattern is rarely lack of effort. Teams usually have plenty of writing. They lack one editor who treats prompts, tool metadata, schemas, migration notes, and docs pages as one connected system instead of five separate chores.
 
 ## FAQ
 
-**How are AI product docs different from ordinary API docs?**
+**Do AI products still need traditional technical writing, or can prompt design replace it?**
 
-AI docs need to explain variability and evaluation, not just syntax. A normal API doc can stop at request shape, auth, and response fields. An AI doc also needs tested scope, known limits, model or prompt assumptions, and whatever tool or retrieval context affects the result.
+Prompt design cannot replace technical writing because prompt design depends on the same inputs a good writer defines: audience, scope, task outcome, constraints, and examples. Google's technical writing material and Anthropic's prompt guidance both point to the same discipline. Someone still has to decide what the system promises and how to state it unambiguously.
 
-**Should technical writers document prompts directly?**
+**Should I create `llms.txt` for every docs site right now?**
 
-I think yes, whenever prompt structure changes output in a meaningful way. Full prompt text is not always necessary, especially for proprietary systems, but the docs should at least expose the versioning model, critical instructions, and any schema or tool assumptions a user needs to reason about behavior.
+I would do it for any product where developers or agents need precise reference material. OpenAI and Google already publish machine-readable docs maps, which tells me the pattern is useful enough in practice to justify maintenance. A bad `llms.txt` file is still better than forcing a model to scrape a maze of navigation and marketing pages.
 
-**Do I need an eval section in product docs?**
+**What part of AI documentation is most undervalued today?**
 
-Serious AI products do. Readers need some credible statement of how quality was assessed. I do not mean a leaderboard screenshot. I mean task-specific criteria, sample distributions, and the failure conditions the team tested. OpenAI's eval guidance is a good baseline for that discipline.
+Tool metadata is the most undervalued surface. OpenAI's docs make clear that metadata affects tool selection and user trust, yet many teams still treat those fields as implementation leftovers. I would put a strong writer or editor directly in that review loop.
 
-**Where should failure modes live?**
+**How much structure is too much?**
 
-I put the most actionable ones directly on the feature or API page, not in a buried troubleshooting article. Setup blockers, unsupported inputs, and common reliability limits belong near the place where a user makes the integration decision.
+Structure becomes harmful when it fragments the task into fifty tiny pages with no editorial hierarchy. Models and humans both need curation. I prefer fewer pages with stronger contracts, explicit examples, and stable machine-readable exports over sprawling doc trees full of near-duplicate fragments.
 
-**What is the biggest mistake teams make right now?**
+**What should a writer ask an AI product team before drafting anything?**
 
-Teams still document AI features like static product surfaces. That misses the real contract. The contract lives in behavior, boundaries, and change management. Once the docs expose those clearly, the product usually becomes easier to trust and easier to operate.
+I would ask five questions first: what exact task does the user need to complete, what inputs are accepted, what outputs are guaranteed, what side effects can happen, and what can fail even when the user did everything right. Clear answers to those questions produce usable docs. Fuzzy answers usually mean the product contract still needs work.
 
