70:OpenAI's [app rules](https://developers.openai.com/apps-sdk/app-submission-guidelines/), Anthropic's [prompting guides](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/build-with-claude/prompt-engineering/overview), and the [MCP specification](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/specification/2025-11-25/server/tools) all keep emphasizing explicitness, validation, and auditable behavior. MCP says clients should validate tool results, log tool usage, show inputs before sensitive calls, and confirm risky operations with the user. OpenAI says tool inputs should be minimal and purpose-driven. Anthropic says prompt engineering should start with clear success criteria and empirical tests. Taken together, those documents point to one writing rule I wish more teams followed: every operational claim in AI docs should map to a testable behavior, not just a plausible sentence.
